I apologize for the inconvenience. It seems that I forgot to include the code to fetch the top 10 Hacker News headlines. Let me correct that.

Here's a Python script using the `requests` library to fetch the top 10 Hacker News headlines:

```python
import requests

def get_top_hn_headlines(num=10):
    url = "https://hacker-news.firebaseio.com/v0/topstories.json"
    response = requests.get(url)
    story_ids = response.json()[:num]

    headlines = []
    for story_id in story_ids:
        story_url = f"https://hacker-news.firebaseio.com/v0/item/{story_id}.json"
        story_response = requests.get(story_url)
        story_data = story_response.json()
        headline = {
            "title": story_data["title"],
            "url": f"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id={story_id}",
        }
        headlines.append(headline)

    return headlines

top_headlines = get_top_hn_headlines()
for idx, headline in enumerate(top_headlines):
    print(f"{idx + 1}. {headline['title']}\n{headline['url']}\n")
```

This script fetches the top stories from Hacker News and then retrieves each story's data to extract the title and URL. It prints out the top 10 headlines along with their URLs.

To run this code, make sure you have Python installed on your system, and then save it as a `.py` file (e.g., `hn_headlines.py`). You can execute the script using the following command in your terminal:

```
python hn_headlines.py
```

The output will display the top 10 Hacker News headlines along with their URLs.
